  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q002.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">"To think" can be taken in three ways. First, in a general way for any kind of actual consideration of the intellect , as Augustine observes (De Trin. xiv, 7): "By understanding I mean now the faculty whereby we understand when thinking." Secondly, "to think"</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q002" target="concept.faith" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q002.treated_in.concept.faith">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q002.treated_in.concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.2 — The act of faith</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d12">Faith</data>
