  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q002.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">The act of any power or habit depends on the relation of that power or habit to its object. Now the object of faith can be considered in three ways. For, since "to believe " is an act of the intellect , in so far as the will moves it to assent, as stated above ( Article 1, R</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q002" target="st.ii-ii.q002.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q002.contains.st.ii-ii.q002.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q002.contains.st.ii-ii.q002.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.2 — The act of faith</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q002.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.2 a.1 — What is "to believe," which is the internal act of faith?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q002.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that to believe is not to think with assent. Because the Latin word "cogitatio" [thought] implies a research, for "cogitare" [to think] seems to be equivalent to "coagitare," i.e. "to discuss together." Now</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q002" target="st.ii-ii.q002.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q002.contains.st.ii-ii.q002.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q002.contains.st.ii-ii.q002.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.2 — The act of faith</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q002.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.2 a.2 — In how many ways is it expressed?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q002.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the act of faith is unsuitably distinguished as believing God , believing in a God , and believing in God . For one habit has but one act. Now faith is one habit since it is one virtue . Therefore it i</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
