  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q004.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that faith does not reside in the intellect . For Augustine says (De Praedest. Sanct. v) that " faith resides in the believer's will." Now the will is a power distinct from the intellect . Therefore faith d</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q004" target="st.ii-ii.q004.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q004.contains.st.ii-ii.q004.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q004.contains.st.ii-ii.q004.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.4 — The virtue itself of faith</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q004.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.4 a.3 — Is its form charity?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q004.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that charity is not the form of faith . For each thing derives its species from its form . When therefore two things are opposite members of a division, one cannot be the form of the other. Now faith and ch</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q004" target="st.ii-ii.q004.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q004.contains.st.ii-ii.q004.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q004.contains.st.ii-ii.q004.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.4 — The virtue itself of faith</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q004.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.4 a.4 — Are living formata faith and lifeless informis faith one identically?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q004.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that lifeless faith does not become living, or living faith lifeless. For, according to 1 Corinthians 13:10 , "when that which is perfect is come, that which is in part shall be done away." Now lifeless fai</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q004" target="st.ii-ii.q004.a005" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q004.contains.st.ii-ii.q004.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q004.contains.st.ii-ii.q004.a005</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.4 — The virtue itself of faith</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q004.a005</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.4 a.5 — Is faith a virtue?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q004.a005.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that faith is not a virtue . For virtue is directed to the good , since "it is virtue that makes its subject good ," as the Philosopher states (Ethic. ii, 6). But faith is directed to the true . Therefore f</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q004" target="st.ii-ii.q004.a006" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q004.contains.st.ii-ii.q004.a006">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q004.contains.st.ii-ii.q004.a006</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.4 — The virtue itself of faith</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q004.a006</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.4 a.6 — Is it one virtue?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q004.a006.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that faith is not one. For just as faith is a gift of God according to Ephesians 2:8 , so also wisdom and knowledge are numbered among God's gifts according to Isaiah 11:2 . Now wisdom and knowledge differ </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q004" target="st.ii-ii.q004.a007" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q004.contains.st.ii-ii.q004.a007">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q004.contains.st.ii-ii.q004.a007</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.4 — The virtue itself of faith</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q004.a007</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.4 a.7 — Its relation to the other virtues</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q004.a007.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that faith is not the first of the virtues . For a gloss on Luke 12:4 , "I say to you My friends," says that fortitude is the foundation of faith . Now the foundation precedes that which is founded thereon.</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q004" target="st.ii-ii.q004.a008" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q004.contains.st.ii-ii.q004.a008">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q004.contains.st.ii-ii.q004.a008</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.4 — The virtue itself of faith</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q004.a008</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.4 a.8 — Its certitude as compared with the certitude of the intellectual virtues</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q004.a008.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that faith is not more certain than science and the other intellectual virtues . For doubt is opposed to certitude , wherefore a thing would seem to be the more certain , through being less doubtful , just </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q005" target="concept.faith" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q005.treated_in.concept.faith">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q005.treated_in.concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q005</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.5 — Those who have faith</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d12">Faith</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q005-treated-in-concept-faith-st-ii-ii-q005-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q005.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Some say that there was no faith in the angels before they were confirmed in grace or fell from it, and in man before he sinned , by reason of the manifest contemplation that they had of Divin</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q005" target="st.ii-ii.q005.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q005.contains.st.ii-ii.q005.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q005.contains.st.ii-ii.q005.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q005</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.5 — Those who have faith</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q005.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.5 a.1 — Was there faith in the angels, or in man, in their original state?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q005.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that there was no faith , either in the angels , or in man , in their original state. For Hugh St. Victor says in his Sentences (De Sacram. i, 10) that " man cannot see God or things that are in God , becau</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q005" target="st.ii-ii.q005.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q005.contains.st.ii-ii.q005.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q005.contains.st.ii-ii.q005.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q005</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.5 — Those who have faith</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q005.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.5 a.2 — Do the demons have faith?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q005.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the demons have no faith . For Augustine says (De Praedest. Sanct. v) that " faith depends on the believer's will": and this is a good will, since by it man wishes to believe in God . Since then no del</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q005" target="st.ii-ii.q005.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q005.contains.st.ii-ii.q005.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q005.contains.st.ii-ii.q005.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q005</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.5 — Those who have faith</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q005.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.5 a.3 — Do those heretics who err in one article, have faith in others?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q005.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that a heretic who disbelieves one article of faith , can have lifeless faith in the other articles. For the natural intellect of a heretic is not more able than that of a catholic. Now a catholic's intelle</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q005" target="st.ii-ii.q005.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q005.contains.st.ii-ii.q005.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q005.contains.st.ii-ii.q005.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q005</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.5 — Those who have faith</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q005.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.5 a.4 — Among those who have faith, does one have it more than another?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q005.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that faith cannot be greater in one man than in another. For the quantity of a habit is taken from its object. Now whoever has faith believes everything that is of faith , since by failing in one point, a m</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q006" target="concept.faith" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q006.treated_in.concept.faith">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q006.treated_in.concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q006</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.6 — The cause of faith</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d12">Faith</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q006-treated-in-concept-faith-st-ii-ii-q006-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q006.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Two things are requisite for faith . First, that the things which are of faith should be proposed to man : this is necessary in order that man believe anything explicitly. The second thing requi</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q006" target="st.ii-ii.q006.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q006.contains.st.ii-ii.q006.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q006.contains.st.ii-ii.q006.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q006</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.6 — The cause of faith</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q006.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.6 a.1 — Is faith infused into man by God?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q006.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that faith is not infused into man by God . For Augustine says (De Trin. xiv) that "science begets faith in us, and nourishes, defends and strengthens it." Now those things which science begets in us seem t</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q006" target="st.ii-ii.q006.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q006.contains.st.ii-ii.q006.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q006.contains.st.ii-ii.q006.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q006</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.6 — The cause of faith</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q006.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.6 a.2 — Is lifeless faith a gift of God?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q006.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that lifeless faith is not a gift of God . For it is written ( Deuteronomy 32:4 ) that "the works of God are perfect." Now lifeless faith is something imperfect. Therefore it is not the work of God .</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q007" target="concept.faith" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q007.treated_in.concept.faith">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q007.treated_in.concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q007</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.7 — The effects of faith</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d12">Faith</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q007-treated-in-concept-faith-st-ii-ii-q007-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q007.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">hended: and consequently the principle of fear and of every appetitive movement must be an apprehension. Again, through faith there arises in us an apprehension of certain penal evils , which are inflicted in accordance with the Divine judgment . On this way, then, faith is a cause of</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q007" target="st.ii-ii.q007.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q007.contains.st.ii-ii.q007.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q007.contains.st.ii-ii.q007.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q007</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.7 — The effects of faith</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q007.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.7 a.1 — Is fear an effect of faith?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q007.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that fear is not an effect of faith . For an effect does not precede its cause . Now fear precedes faith : for it is written ( Sirach 2:8 ): "Ye that fear the Lord, believe in Him." Therefore fear is not an</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q007" target="st.ii-ii.q007.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q007.contains.st.ii-ii.q007.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q007.contains.st.ii-ii.q007.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q007</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.7 — The effects of faith</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q007.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.7 a.2 — Is the heart purified by faith?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q007.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that faith does not purify the heart. For purity of the heart pertains chiefly to the affections, whereas faith is in the intellect . Therefore faith has not the effect of purifying the heart.</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q008" target="concept.faith" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q008.treated_in.concept.faith">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q008.treated_in.concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.8 — The gift of understanding</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d12">Faith</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q008-treated-in-concept-faith-st-ii-ii-q008-a008-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q008.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">nging to the will . On this way we must conclude that the fruit which properly responds to the gift of understanding is faith , i.e. the certitude of faith ; while the fruit that responds to it last of all is joy , which belongs to the will .</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q008" target="concept.understanding_gift" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q008.treated_in.concept.understanding_gift">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q008.treated_in.concept.understanding_gift</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.8 — The gift of understanding</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.understanding_gift</data>
  <data key="d12">Gift of Understanding</data>
  <data key="d13">gift_holy_spirit</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q008-treated-in-concept-understanding-gift-st-ii-ii-q008-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q008.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">as to know what it cannot know by its natural light: and this supernatural light which is bestowed on man is called the gift of understanding.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q008" target="st.ii-ii.q008.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q008.contains.st.ii-ii.q008.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q008.contains.st.ii-ii.q008.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.8 — The gift of understanding</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q008.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.8 a.1 — Is understanding a gift of the Holy Ghost?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q008.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that understanding is not a gift of the Holy Ghost . For the gifts of grace are distinct from the gifts of nature , since they are given in addition to the latter. Now understanding is a natural habit of th</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q008" target="st.ii-ii.q008.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q008.contains.st.ii-ii.q008.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q008.contains.st.ii-ii.q008.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.8 — The gift of understanding</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q008.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.8 a.2 — Can it be together with faith in the same person?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q008.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the gift of understanding is incompatible with faith . For Augustine says (QQ. lxxxiii, qu. 15) that "the thing which is understood is bounded by the comprehension of him who understands it." But the t</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q008" target="st.ii-ii.q008.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q008.contains.st.ii-ii.q008.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q008.contains.st.ii-ii.q008.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.8 — The gift of understanding</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q008.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.8 a.3 — Is the understanding which is a gift of the Holy Ghost, only speculative, or practical also?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q008.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that understanding, considered as a gift of the Holy Ghost , is not practical, but only speculative. For, according to Gregory (Moral. i, 32), "understanding penetrates certain more exalted things." But the</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q008" target="st.ii-ii.q008.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q008.contains.st.ii-ii.q008.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q008.contains.st.ii-ii.q008.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.8 — The gift of understanding</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q008.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.8 a.4 — Do all who are in a state of grace have the gift of understanding?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q008.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the gift of understanding is not in all who are in a state of grace . For Gregory says (Moral. ii, 49) that "the gift of understanding is given as a remedy against dulness of mind." Now many who are in</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q008" target="st.ii-ii.q008.a005" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q008.contains.st.ii-ii.q008.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q008.contains.st.ii-ii.q008.a005</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.8 — The gift of understanding</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q008.a005</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.8 a.5 — Is this gift to be found in those who are without grace?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q008.a005.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the gift of understanding is found also in those who have not sanctifying grace . For Augustine , in expounding the words of Psalm 118:20 : "My soul hath coveted to long for Thy justifications," says: </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q008" target="st.ii-ii.q008.a006" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q008.contains.st.ii-ii.q008.a006">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q008.contains.st.ii-ii.q008.a006</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.8 — The gift of understanding</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q008.a006</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.8 a.6 — The relationship of the gift of understanding to the other gifts</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q008.a006.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the gift of understanding is not distinct from the other gifts . For there is no distinction between things whose opposites are not distinct. Now "wisdom is contrary to folly, understanding is contrary</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q008" target="st.ii-ii.q008.a007" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q008.contains.st.ii-ii.q008.a007">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q008.contains.st.ii-ii.q008.a007</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.8 — The gift of understanding</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q008.a007</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.8 a.7 — Which of the beatitudes corresponds to this gift?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q008.a007.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the sixth beatitude, "Blessed are the clean of heart, for they shall see God ," does not respond to the gift of understanding. Because cleanness of heart seems to belong chiefly to the appetite . But t</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q008" target="st.ii-ii.q008.a008" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q008.contains.st.ii-ii.q008.a008">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q008.contains.st.ii-ii.q008.a008</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.8 — The gift of understanding</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q008.a008</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.8 a.8 — Which of the fruits?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q008.a008.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that, among the fruits, faith does not respond to the gift of understanding. For understanding is the fruit of faith , since it is written ( Isaiah 7:9 ) according to another reading [the Septuagint ]: "If </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q009" target="concept.faith" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q009.treated_in.concept.faith">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q009.treated_in.concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q009</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.9 — The gift of knowledge</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d12">Faith</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q009-treated-in-concept-faith-st-ii-ii-q009-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q009.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">on it. Accordingly, two things are requisite in order that the human intellect may perfectly assent to the truth of the faith : one of these is that he should have a sound grasp of the things that are proposed to be believed , and this pertains to the gift of understanding, as stated</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q009" target="concept.knowledge_gift" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q009.treated_in.concept.knowledge_gift">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q009.treated_in.concept.knowledge_gift</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q009</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.9 — The gift of knowledge</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.knowledge_gift</data>
  <data key="d12">Gift of Knowledge</data>
  <data key="d13">gift_holy_spirit</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q009-treated-in-concept-knowledge-gift-st-ii-ii-q009-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q009.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">nd right judgment on them, so as to discern what is to be believed , from what is not to be believed , and for this the gift of knowledge is required.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q009" target="st.ii-ii.q009.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q009.contains.st.ii-ii.q009.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q009.contains.st.ii-ii.q009.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q009</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.9 — The gift of knowledge</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q009.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.9 a.1 — Is knowledge a gift?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q009.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that knowledge is not a gift . For the gifts of the Holy Ghost surpass the natural faculty. But knowledge implies an effect of natural reason : for the Philosopher says (Poster. i, 2) that a "demonstration </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q009" target="st.ii-ii.q009.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q009.contains.st.ii-ii.q009.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q009.contains.st.ii-ii.q009.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q009</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.9 — The gift of knowledge</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q009.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.9 a.2 — Is it about Divine things?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q009.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the gift of knowledge is about Divine things. For Augustine says (De Trin. xiv, 1) that " knowledge begets, nourishes and strengthens faith ." Now faith is about Divine things, because its object is th</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q009" target="st.ii-ii.q009.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q009.contains.st.ii-ii.q009.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q009.contains.st.ii-ii.q009.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q009</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.9 — The gift of knowledge</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q009.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.9 a.3 — Is it speculative or practical?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q009.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the knowledge , which is numbered among the gifts , is practical knowledge . For Augustine says (De Trin. xii, 14) that " knowledge is concerned with the actions in which we make use of external things</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q009" target="st.ii-ii.q009.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q009.contains.st.ii-ii.q009.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q009.contains.st.ii-ii.q009.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q009</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.9 — The gift of knowledge</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q009.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.9 a.4 — Which beatitude corresponds to it?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q009.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the third beatitude, "Blessed are they that mourn," does not correspond to the gift of knowledge . For, even as evil is the cause of sorrow and grief, so is good the cause of joy . Now knowledge brings</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q010" target="concept.faith" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q010.treated_in.concept.faith">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q010.treated_in.concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q010</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.10 — Unbelief in general</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d12">Faith</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q010-treated-in-concept-faith-st-ii-ii-q010-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q010.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">taken in two ways: first, by way of pure negation, so that a man be called an unbeliever, merely because he has not the faith . Secondly, unbelief may be taken by way of opposition to the faith ; in which sense a man refuses to hear the faith , or despises it, according to Isaiah 53:1</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q010" target="concept.unbelief" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q010.treated_in.concept.unbelief">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q010.treated_in.concept.unbelief</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q010</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.10 — Unbelief in general</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.unbelief</data>
  <data key="d12">Unbelief</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q010-treated-in-concept-unbelief-st-ii-ii-q010-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q010.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Unbelief may be taken in two ways: first, by way of pure negation, so that a man be called an unbeliever, merely because he has not the faith . Secondly, unbelief may b</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q010" target="st.ii-ii.q010.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q010.contains.st.ii-ii.q010.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q010.contains.st.ii-ii.q010.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q010</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.10 — Unbelief in general</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q010.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.10 a.1 — Is unbelief a sin?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q010.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that unbelief is not a sin . For every sin is contrary to nature , as Damascene proves (De Fide Orth. ii, 4). Now unbelief seems not to be contrary to nature ; for Augustine says (De Praedest. Sanct. v) tha</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q010" target="st.ii-ii.q010.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q010.contains.st.ii-ii.q010.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q010.contains.st.ii-ii.q010.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q010</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.10 — Unbelief in general</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q010.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.10 a.2 — What is its subject?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q010.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that unbelief is not in the intellect as its subject. For every sin is in the will , according to Augustine (De Duabus Anim. x, xi). Now unbelief is a sin , as stated above ( Article 1 ). Therefore unbelief</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q010" target="st.ii-ii.q010.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q010.contains.st.ii-ii.q010.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q010.contains.st.ii-ii.q010.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q010</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.10 — Unbelief in general</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q010.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.10 a.3 — Is it the greatest of sins?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q010.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that unbelief is not the greatest of sins . For Augustine says (De Bapt. contra Donat. iv, 20): "I should hesitate to decide whether a very wicked Catholic ought to be preferred to a heretic , in whose life</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q010" target="st.ii-ii.q010.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q010.contains.st.ii-ii.q010.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q010.contains.st.ii-ii.q010.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q010</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.10 — Unbelief in general</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q010.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.10 a.4 — Is every action of unbelievers a sin?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q010.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that each act of an unbeliever is a sin . Because a gloss on Romans 14:23 , "All that is not of faith is sin ," says: "The whole life of unbelievers is a sin ." Now the life of unbelievers consists of their</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q010" target="st.ii-ii.q010.a005" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q010.contains.st.ii-ii.q010.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q010.contains.st.ii-ii.q010.a005</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q010</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.10 — Unbelief in general</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q010.a005</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.10 a.5 — The species of unbelief</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q010.a005.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that there are not several species of unbelief. For, since faith and unbelief are contrary to one another, they must be about the same thing. Now the formal object of faith is the First Truth, whence it der</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q010" target="st.ii-ii.q010.a006" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q010.contains.st.ii-ii.q010.a006">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q010.contains.st.ii-ii.q010.a006</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q010</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.10 — Unbelief in general</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q010.a006</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.10 a.6 — Their comparison, one with another</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q010.a006.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the unbelief of heathens or pagans is graver than other kinds. For just as bodily disease is graver according as it endangers the health of a more important member of the body, so does sin appear to be</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q010" target="st.ii-ii.q010.a007" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q010.contains.st.ii-ii.q010.a007">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q010.contains.st.ii-ii.q010.a007</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q010</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.10 — Unbelief in general</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q010.a007</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.10 a.7 — Should we dispute about faith with unbelievers?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q010.a007.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that one ought not to dispute with unbelievers in public. For the Apostle says ( 2 Timothy 2:14 ): "Contend not in words, for it is to no profit, but to the subverting of the hearers." But it is impossible </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q010" target="st.ii-ii.q010.a008" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q010.contains.st.ii-ii.q010.a008">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q010.contains.st.ii-ii.q010.a008</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q010</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.10 — Unbelief in general</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q010.a008</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.10 a.8 — Should they be compelled to the faith?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q010.a008.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that unbelievers ought by no means to be compelled to the faith . For it is written ( Matthew 13:28 ) that the servants of the householder, in whose field cockle had been sown, asked him: "Wilt thou that we</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q010" target="st.ii-ii.q010.a009" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q010.contains.st.ii-ii.q010.a009">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q010.contains.st.ii-ii.q010.a009</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q010</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.10 — Unbelief in general</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q010.a009</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.10 a.9 — Should we have communications with them?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q010.a009.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that it is lawful to communicate with unbelievers. For the Apostle says ( 1 Corinthians 10:27 ): "If any of them that believe not, invite you, and you be willing to go, eat of anything that is set before yo</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q010" target="st.ii-ii.q010.a010" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q010.contains.st.ii-ii.q010.a010">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q010.contains.st.ii-ii.q010.a010</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q010</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.10 — Unbelief in general</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q010.a010</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.10 a.10 — Can unbelievers have authority over Christians?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q010.a010.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that unbelievers may have authority or dominion over the faithful. For the Apostle says ( 1 Timothy 6:1 ): "Whosoever are servants under the yoke, let them count their masters worthy of all honor ": and it </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q010" target="st.ii-ii.q010.a011" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q010.contains.st.ii-ii.q010.a011">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q010.contains.st.ii-ii.q010.a011</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q010</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.10 — Unbelief in general</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q010.a011</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.10 a.11 — Should the rites of unbelievers be tolerated?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q010.a011.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that rites of unbelievers ought not to be tolerated. For it is evident that unbelievers sin in observing their rites: and not to prevent a sin , when one can, seems to imply consent therein, as a gloss obse</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q010" target="st.ii-ii.q010.a012" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q010.contains.st.ii-ii.q010.a012">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q010.contains.st.ii-ii.q010.a012</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q010</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.10 — Unbelief in general</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q010.a012</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.10 a.12 — Are the children of unbelievers to be baptized against their parents' will?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q010.a012.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the children of Jews and of other unbelievers ought to be baptized against their parents' will. For the bond of marriage is stronger than the right of parental authority over children, since the right </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q011" target="concept.heresy" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q011.treated_in.concept.heresy">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q011.treated_in.concept.heresy</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q011</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.11 — Heresy</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.heresy</data>
  <data key="d12">Heresy</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q011-treated-in-concept-heresy-st-ii-ii-q011-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q011.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">The word heresy as stated in the first objection denotes a choosing. Now choice as stated above ( I-II:13:3 ) is about things directed to the end, the end being presupposed. N</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q011" target="concept.unbelief" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q011.treated_in.concept.unbelief">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q011.treated_in.concept.unbelief</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q011</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.11 — Heresy</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.unbelief</data>
  <data key="d12">Unbelief</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q011-treated-in-concept-unbelief-st-ii-ii-q011-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q011.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">e character of being directed to the end. Now, whoever believes , assents to someone's words; so that, in every form of unbelief, the person to whose words assent is given seems to hold the chief place and to be the end as it were; while the things by holding which one assents to that pe</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q011" target="st.ii-ii.q011.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q011.contains.st.ii-ii.q011.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q011.contains.st.ii-ii.q011.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q011</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.11 — Heresy</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q011.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.11 a.1 — Is heresy a kind of unbelief?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q011.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that heresy is not a species of unbelief. For unbelief is in the understanding, as stated above ( II-II:10:2 ). Now heresy would seem not to pertain to the understanding, but rather to the appetitive power;</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q011" target="st.ii-ii.q011.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q011.contains.st.ii-ii.q011.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q011.contains.st.ii-ii.q011.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q011</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.11 — Heresy</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q011.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.11 a.2 — The matter about which it is</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q011.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that heresy is not properly about matters of faith . For just as there are heresies and sects among Christians , so were there among the Jews , and Pharisees , as Isidore observes (Etym. viii, 3,4,5). Now t</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q011" target="st.ii-ii.q011.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q011.contains.st.ii-ii.q011.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q011.contains.st.ii-ii.q011.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q011</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.11 — Heresy</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q011.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.11 a.3 — Should heretics be tolerated?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q011.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It seems that heretics ought to be tolerated. For the Apostle says ( 2 Timothy 2:24-25 ): "The servant of the Lord must not wrangle . . . with modesty admonishing them that resist the truth , if peradventure God may give</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q011" target="st.ii-ii.q011.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q011.contains.st.ii-ii.q011.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q011.contains.st.ii-ii.q011.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q011</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.11 — Heresy</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q011.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.11 a.4 — Should converts be received?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q011.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the Church ought in all cases to receive those who return from heresy . For it is written ( Jeremiah 3:1 ) in the person of the Lord: "Thou hast prostituted thyself to many lovers; nevertheless return </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q012" target="concept.apostasy" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q012.treated_in.concept.apostasy">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q012.treated_in.concept.apostasy</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q012</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.12 — Apostasy</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.apostasy</data>
  <data key="d12">Apostasy</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q012-treated-in-concept-apostasy-st-ii-ii-q012-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q012.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Apostasy denotes a backsliding from God . This may happen in various ways according to the different kinds of union between man and God . For, in the first place, man i</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q012" target="concept.unbelief" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q012.treated_in.concept.unbelief">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q012.treated_in.concept.unbelief</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q012</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.12 — Apostasy</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.unbelief</data>
  <data key="d12">Unbelief</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q012-treated-in-concept-unbelief-st-ii-ii-q012-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q012.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">man withdraws from the faith , and is called "apostasy of perfidy." On this way apostasy, simply so called, pertains to unbelief.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q012" target="st.ii-ii.q012.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q012.contains.st.ii-ii.q012.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q012.contains.st.ii-ii.q012.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q012</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.12 — Apostasy</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q012.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.12 a.1 — Does apostasy pertain to unbelief?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q012.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that apostasy does not pertain to unbelief. For that which is the origin of all sins , does not, seemingly, pertain to unbelief, since many sins there are without unbelief. Now apostasy seems to be the orig</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q012" target="st.ii-ii.q012.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q012.contains.st.ii-ii.q012.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q012.contains.st.ii-ii.q012.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q012</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.12 — Apostasy</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q012.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.12 a.2 — On account of apostasy from the faith, are subjects absolved from allegiance to an apostate prince?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q012.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that a prince does not so forfeit his dominion over his subjects, on account of apostasy from the faith , that they no longer owe him allegiance. For Ambrose [ St. Augustine , Super Psalm 124:3 says that th</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q013" target="concept.blasphemy" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q013.treated_in.concept.blasphemy">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q013.treated_in.concept.blasphemy</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q013</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.13 — The sin of blasphemy, in general</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.blasphemy</data>
  <data key="d12">Blasphemy</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q013-treated-in-concept-blasphemy-st-ii-ii-q013-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q013.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">The word blasphemy seems to denote the disparagement of some surpassing goodness , especially that of God . Now God , as Dionysius says (Div. Nom. i), is the very essence of true</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q013" target="concept.confession_of_faith" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q013.treated_in.concept.confession_of_faith">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q013.treated_in.concept.confession_of_faith</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q013</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.13 — The sin of blasphemy, in general</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.confession_of_faith</data>
  <data key="d12">Confession of Faith</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q013-treated-in-concept-confession-of-faith-st-ii-ii-q013-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q013.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">ught only, it is blasphemy of the heart, whereas if it betrays itself outwardly in speech it is blasphemy is opposed to confession of faith .</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q013" target="st.ii-ii.q013.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q013.contains.st.ii-ii.q013.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q013.contains.st.ii-ii.q013.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q013</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.13 — The sin of blasphemy, in general</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q013.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.13 a.1 — Is blasphemy opposed to the confession of faith?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q013.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that blasphemy is not opposed to the confession of faith . Because to blaspheme is to utter an affront or insult against the Creator . Now this pertains to ill-will against God rather than to unbelief. Ther</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q013" target="st.ii-ii.q013.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q013.contains.st.ii-ii.q013.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q013.contains.st.ii-ii.q013.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q013</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.13 — The sin of blasphemy, in general</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q013.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.13 a.2 — Is blasphemy always a mortal sin?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q013.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that blasphemy is not always a mortal sin . Because a gloss on the words, "Now lay you also all away," etc. ( Colossians 3:8 ) says: "After prohibiting greater crimes he forbids lesser sins ": and yet among</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q013" target="st.ii-ii.q013.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q013.contains.st.ii-ii.q013.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q013.contains.st.ii-ii.q013.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q013</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.13 — The sin of blasphemy, in general</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q013.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.13 a.3 — Is blasphemy the most grievous sin?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q013.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the sin of blasphemy is not the greatest sin . For, according to Augustine (Enchiridion xii), a thing is said to be evil because it does harm. Now the sin of murder , since it destroys a man's life, do</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q013" target="st.ii-ii.q013.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q013.contains.st.ii-ii.q013.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q013.contains.st.ii-ii.q013.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q013</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.13 — The sin of blasphemy, in general</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q013.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.13 a.4 — Is blasphemy in the damned?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q013.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the damned do not blaspheme . Because some wicked men are deterred from blaspheming now, on account of the fear of future punishment. But the damned are undergoing these punishments, so that they abhor</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q014" target="concept.blasphemy_against_holy_spirit" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q014.treated_in.concept.blasphemy_against_holy_spirit">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q014.treated_in.concept.blasphemy_against_holy_spirit</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q014</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.14 — Blasphemy against the Holy Ghost</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.blasphemy_against_holy_spirit</data>
  <data key="d12">Sin Against the Holy Spirit</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q014-treated-in-concept-blasphemy-against-holy-spirit-st-ii-ii-q014-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q014.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Three meanings have been given to the sin against the Holy Ghost . For the earlier doctors , viz. Athanasius (Super Matth. xii, 32), Hilary (Can. xii in Matth.), Ambrose (Super Luc. xii, 10), Jerome (Super Matth. xii), and C</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q014" target="concept.holy_spirit" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q014.treated_in.concept.holy_spirit">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q014.treated_in.concept.holy_spirit</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q014</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.14 — Blasphemy against the Holy Ghost</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.holy_spirit</data>
  <data key="d12">Holy Spirit</data>
  <data key="d13">doctrine</data>
