  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q017-treated-in-concept-eternal-life-st-ii-ii-q017-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q017.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Hope, as stated above ( Article 1 ; I-II:40:7 ), regards two things, viz. the good which it intends to obtain, and the help by which that good is obtained. Now the good which a man hopes to obtain, has the aspect of a final cause , while the help by which one</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q017" target="concept.hope" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q017.treated_in.concept.hope">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q017.treated_in.concept.hope</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q017</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.17 — Hope, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.hope</data>
  <data key="d12">Hope</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q017-treated-in-concept-hope-st-ii-ii-q017-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q017.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">emote and excelling, viz. God : wherefore every human act is good , which attains reason or God Himself. Now the act of hope, whereof we speak now, attains God . For, as we have already stated ( I-II:40:1 ), when we were treating of the passion of hope, the object of hope is a future</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q017" target="st.ii-ii.q017.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q017.contains.st.ii-ii.q017.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q017.contains.st.ii-ii.q017.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q017</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.17 — Hope, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q017.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.17 a.1 — Is hope a virtue?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q017.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that hope is not a virtue . For "no man makes ill use of a virtue ," as Augustine states (De Lib. Arb. ii, 18). But one may make ill use of hope, since the passion of hope, like the other passions , is subj</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q017" target="st.ii-ii.q017.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q017.contains.st.ii-ii.q017.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q017.contains.st.ii-ii.q017.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q017</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.17 — Hope, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q017.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.17 a.2 — Is its object eternal happiness?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q017.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that eternal happiness is not the proper object of hope. For a man does not hope for that which surpasses every movement of the soul , since hope itself is a movement of the soul . Now eternal happiness sur</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q017" target="st.ii-ii.q017.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q017.contains.st.ii-ii.q017.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q017.contains.st.ii-ii.q017.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q017</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.17 — Hope, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q017.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.17 a.3 — May one man, by the virtue of hope, hope for another's happiness?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q017.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that one may hope for another's eternal happiness . For the Apostle says ( Philippians 1:6 ): "Being confident of this very thing, that He Who hath begun a good work in you, will perfect it unto the day of </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q017" target="st.ii-ii.q017.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q017.contains.st.ii-ii.q017.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q017.contains.st.ii-ii.q017.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q017</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.17 — Hope, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q017.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.17 a.4 — May a man lawfully hope in man?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q017.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that one may lawfully hope in man . For the object of hope is eternal happiness . Now we are helped to obtain eternal happiness by the patronage of the saints , for Gregory says (Dial. i, 8) that " predesti</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q017" target="st.ii-ii.q017.a005" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q017.contains.st.ii-ii.q017.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q017.contains.st.ii-ii.q017.a005</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q017</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.17 — Hope, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q017.a005</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.17 a.5 — Is hope a theological virtue?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q017.a005.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that hope is not a theological virtue . For a theological virtue is one that has God for its object. Now hope has for its object not only God but also other goods which we hope to obtain from God . Therefor</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q017" target="st.ii-ii.q017.a006" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q017.contains.st.ii-ii.q017.a006">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q017.contains.st.ii-ii.q017.a006</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q017</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.17 — Hope, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q017.a006</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.17 a.6 — Its distinction from the other theological virtues</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q017.a006.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that hope is not distinct from the other theological virtues . For habits are distinguished by their objects, as stated above ( I-II:54:2 ). Now the object of hope is the same as of the other theological vi</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q017" target="st.ii-ii.q017.a007" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q017.contains.st.ii-ii.q017.a007">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q017.contains.st.ii-ii.q017.a007</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q017</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.17 — Hope, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q017.a007</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.17 a.7 — Its relation to faith</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q017.a007.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that hope precedes faith . Because a gloss on Psalm 36:3 , "Trust in the Lord, and do good ," says: "Hope is the entrance to faith and the beginning of salvation ." But salvation is by faith whereby we are </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q017" target="st.ii-ii.q017.a008" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q017.contains.st.ii-ii.q017.a008">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q017.contains.st.ii-ii.q017.a008</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q017</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.17 — Hope, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q017.a008</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.17 a.8 — Its relation to charity</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q017.a008.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that charity precedes hope. For Ambrose says on Luke 17:6 , "If you had faith like to a grain of mustard seed," etc.: " Charity flows from faith , and hope from charity ." But faith precedes charity . There</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q018" target="concept.hope" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q018.treated_in.concept.hope">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q018.treated_in.concept.hope</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q018</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.18 — The subject of hope</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.hope</data>
  <data key="d12">Hope</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q018-treated-in-concept-hope-st-ii-ii-q018-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q018.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As shown above ( I:87:2 ), habits are known by their acts. Now the act of hope is a movement of the appetitive faculty, since its object is a good . And, since there is a twofold appetite in man , namely, the sensitive which is divided in</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q018" target="concept.will" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q018.treated_in.concept.will">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q018.treated_in.concept.will</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q018</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.18 — The subject of hope</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.will</data>
  <data key="d12">Will</data>
  <data key="d13">faculty</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q018-treated-in-concept-will-st-ii-ii-q018-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q018.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">, namely, the sensitive which is divided into irascible and concupiscible , and the intellective appetite , called the will , as stated in I:82:5 , those movements which occur in the lower appetite , are with passion, while those in the higher appetite are without passion, as shown</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q018" target="st.ii-ii.q018.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q018.contains.st.ii-ii.q018.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q018.contains.st.ii-ii.q018.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q018</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.18 — The subject of hope</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q018.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.18 a.1 — Is the virtue of hope in the will as its subject?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q018.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that hope is not in the will as its subject. For the object of hope is an arduous good , as stated above ( II-II:17:1 ; I-II:40:1 ). Now the arduous is the object, not of the will , but of the irascible. Th</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q018" target="st.ii-ii.q018.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q018.contains.st.ii-ii.q018.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q018.contains.st.ii-ii.q018.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q018</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.18 — The subject of hope</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q018.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.18 a.2 — Is it in the blessed?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q018.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that in the blessed there is hope. For Christ was a perfect comprehensor from the first moment of His conception. Now He had hope, since, according to a gloss , the words of Psalm 30:2 , "In Thee, O Lord, h</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q018" target="st.ii-ii.q018.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q018.contains.st.ii-ii.q018.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q018.contains.st.ii-ii.q018.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q018</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.18 — The subject of hope</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q018.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.18 a.3 — Is it in the damned?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q018.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that there is hope in the damned. For the devil is damned and prince of the damned, according to Matthew 25:41 : "Depart . . . you cursed , into everlasting fire, which was prepared for the devil and his an</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q018" target="st.ii-ii.q018.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q018.contains.st.ii-ii.q018.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q018.contains.st.ii-ii.q018.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q018</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.18 — The subject of hope</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q018.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.18 a.4 — Is there certainty in the hope of the wayfarer?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q018.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that there is no certainty in the hope of a wayfarer. For hope resides in the will . But certainty pertains not to the will but to the intellect . Therefore there is no certainty in hope.</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q019" target="concept.fear_of_lord_gift" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q019.treated_in.concept.fear_of_lord_gift">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q019.treated_in.concept.fear_of_lord_gift</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q019</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.19 — The gift of fear</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.fear_of_lord_gift</data>
  <data key="d12">Gift of Fear of the Lord</data>
  <data key="d13">gift_holy_spirit</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q019-treated-in-concept-fear-of-lord-gift-st-ii-ii-q019-a009-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q019.a009.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Fear is of several kinds, as stated above ( Article 2 ). Now it is not " human fear," according to Augustine (De Gratia et Lib. Arb. xviii), "that is a gift of God "—for it was by this fear that Peter denied Christ—but that fear of which it was said ( Matthew</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q019" target="concept.hope" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q019.treated_in.concept.hope">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q019.treated_in.concept.hope</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q019</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.19 — The gift of fear</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.hope</data>
  <data key="d12">Hope</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q019-treated-in-concept-hope-st-ii-ii-q019-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q019.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Just as hope has two objects, one of which is the future good itself, that one expects to obtain, while the other is someone's help, through whom one expects to obtain what</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q019" target="st.ii-ii.q019.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q019.contains.st.ii-ii.q019.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q019.contains.st.ii-ii.q019.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q019</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.19 — The gift of fear</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q019.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.19 a.1 — Is God to be feared?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q019.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that God cannot be feared. For the object of fear is a future evil , as stated above ( I-II:41:2 ; I-II:41:3 ). But God is free of all evil , since He is goodness itself. Therefore God cannot be feared.</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q019" target="st.ii-ii.q019.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q019.contains.st.ii-ii.q019.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q019.contains.st.ii-ii.q019.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q019</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.19 — The gift of fear</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q019.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.19 a.2 — The division of fear into filial, initial, servile and worldly</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q019.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that fear is unfittingly divided into filial, initial, servile and worldly fear. For Damascene says (De Fide Orth. ii, 15) that there are six kinds of fear, viz. "laziness, shamefacedness," etc. of which we</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q019" target="st.ii-ii.q019.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q019.contains.st.ii-ii.q019.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q019.contains.st.ii-ii.q019.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q019</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.19 — The gift of fear</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q019.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.19 a.3 — Is worldly fear always evil?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q019.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that worldly fear is not always evil . Because regard for men seems to be a kind of human fear. Now some are blamed for having no regard for man , for instance, the unjust judge of whom we read ( Luke 18:2 </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q019" target="st.ii-ii.q019.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q019.contains.st.ii-ii.q019.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q019.contains.st.ii-ii.q019.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q019</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.19 — The gift of fear</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q019.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.19 a.4 — Is servile fear good?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q019.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that servile fear is not good . For if the use of a thing is evil , the thing itself is evil . Now the use of servile fear is evil , for according to a gloss on Romans 8:15 , "if a man do anything through f</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q019" target="st.ii-ii.q019.a005" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q019.contains.st.ii-ii.q019.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q019.contains.st.ii-ii.q019.a005</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q019</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.19 — The gift of fear</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q019.a005</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.19 a.5 — Is it substantially the same as filial fear?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q019.a005.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that servile fear is substantially the same as filial fear. For filial fear is to servile fear the same apparently as living faith is to lifeless faith , since the one is accompanied by mortal sin and the o</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q019" target="st.ii-ii.q019.a006" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q019.contains.st.ii-ii.q019.a006">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q019.contains.st.ii-ii.q019.a006</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q019</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.19 — The gift of fear</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q019.a006</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.19 a.6 — Does servile fear depart when charity comes?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q019.a006.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that servile fear does not remain with charity . For Augustine says (In prim. canon. Joan. Tract. ix) that "when charity takes up its abode, it drives away fear which had prepared a place for it."</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q019" target="st.ii-ii.q019.a007" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q019.contains.st.ii-ii.q019.a007">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q019.contains.st.ii-ii.q019.a007</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q019</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.19 — The gift of fear</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q019.a007</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.19 a.7 — Is fear the beginning of wisdom?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q019.a007.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that fear is not the beginning of wisdom. For the beginning of a thing is a part thereof. But fear is not a part of wisdom, since fear is seated in the appetitive faculty, while wisdom is in the intellect .</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q019" target="st.ii-ii.q019.a008" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q019.contains.st.ii-ii.q019.a008">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q019.contains.st.ii-ii.q019.a008</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q019</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.19 — The gift of fear</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q019.a008</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.19 a.8 — Is initial fear substantially the same as filial fear?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q019.a008.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that initial fear differs substantially from filial fear. For filial fear is caused by love. Now initial fear is the beginning of love, according to Sirach 25:16 , "The fear of God is the beginning of love.</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q019" target="st.ii-ii.q019.a009" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q019.contains.st.ii-ii.q019.a009">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q019.contains.st.ii-ii.q019.a009</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q019</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.19 — The gift of fear</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q019.a009</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.19 a.9 — Is fear a gift of the Holy Ghost?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q019.a009.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that fear is not a gift of the Holy Ghost . For no gift of the Holy Ghost is opposed to a virtue , which is also from the Holy Ghost ; else the Holy Ghost would be in opposition to Himself. Now fear is oppo</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q019" target="st.ii-ii.q019.a010" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q019.contains.st.ii-ii.q019.a010">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q019.contains.st.ii-ii.q019.a010</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q019</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.19 — The gift of fear</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q019.a010</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.19 a.10 — Does it grow when charity grows?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q019.a010.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It seems that fear decreases when charity increases. For Augustine says (In prim. canon. Joan. Tract. ix): "The more charity increases, the more fear decreases."</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q019" target="st.ii-ii.q019.a011" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q019.contains.st.ii-ii.q019.a011">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q019.contains.st.ii-ii.q019.a011</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q019</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.19 — The gift of fear</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q019.a011</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.19 a.11 — Does it remain in heaven?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q019.a011.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that fear does not remain in heaven . For it is written ( Proverbs 1:33 ): "He . . . shall enjoy abundance, without fear of evils ," which is to be understood as referring to those who already enjoy wisdom </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q019" target="st.ii-ii.q019.a012" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q019.contains.st.ii-ii.q019.a012">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q019.contains.st.ii-ii.q019.a012</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q019</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.19 — The gift of fear</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q019.a012</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.19 a.12 — Which of the beatitudes and fruits correspond to it?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q019.a012.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that poverty of spirit is not the beatitude corresponding to the gift of fear. For fear is the beginning of the spiritual life, as explained above ( Article 7 ): whereas poverty belongs to the perfection of</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q020" target="concept.despair_sin" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q020.treated_in.concept.despair_sin">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q020.treated_in.concept.despair_sin</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q020</data>
