  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q020.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.20 a.1 — Is despair a sin?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q020.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that despair is not a sin . For every sin includes conversion to a mutable good , together with aversion from the immutable good , as Augustine states (De Lib. Arb. ii, 19). But despair includes no conversi</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q020" target="st.ii-ii.q020.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q020.contains.st.ii-ii.q020.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q020.contains.st.ii-ii.q020.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q020</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.20 — Despair</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q020.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.20 a.2 — Can it be without unbelief?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q020.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that there can be no despair without unbelief. For the certainty of hope is derived from faith ; and so long as the cause remains the effect is not done away. Therefore a man cannot lose the certainty of ho</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q020" target="st.ii-ii.q020.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q020.contains.st.ii-ii.q020.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q020.contains.st.ii-ii.q020.a003</data>
