  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q024.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that charity is infused according to the capacity of our natural gifts . For it is written ( Matthew 25:15 ) that "He gave to every one according to his own virtue [ Douay : 'proper ability']." Now, in man </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q024" target="st.ii-ii.q024.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q024.contains.st.ii-ii.q024.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q024.contains.st.ii-ii.q024.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q024</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.24 — The subject of charity</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q024.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.24 a.4 — Does it increase in the person who has it?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q024.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that charity cannot increase. For nothing increases save what has quantity . Now quantity is twofold, namely dimensive and virtual. The former does not befit charity which is a spiritual perfection, while v</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q024" target="st.ii-ii.q024.a005" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q024.contains.st.ii-ii.q024.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q024.contains.st.ii-ii.q024.a005</data>
