  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q026.a012.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that a man ought to love his benefactor more than one he has benefited. For Augustine says (De Catech. Rud. iv): "Nothing will incite another more to love you than that you love him first: for he must have </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q026" target="st.ii-ii.q026.a013" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q026.contains.st.ii-ii.q026.a013">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q026.contains.st.ii-ii.q026.a013</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q026</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.26 — The order of charity</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q026.a013</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.26 a.13 — Does the order of charity endure in heaven?</data>
