<edge source="st.ii-ii.q027" target="st.ii-ii.q027.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q027.contains.st.ii-ii.q027.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q027.contains.st.ii-ii.q027.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q027</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.27 — The principle act of charity, which is to love</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q027.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.27 a.1 — Which is the more proper to charity, to love or to be loved?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q027.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that it is more proper to charity to be loved than to love. For the better charity is to be found in those who are themselves better. But those who are better should be more loved. Therefore to be loved is </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q027" target="st.ii-ii.q027.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q027.contains.st.ii-ii.q027.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q027.contains.st.ii-ii.q027.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q027</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.27 — The principle act of charity, which is to love</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q027.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.27 a.2 — Is to love considered as an act of charity the same as goodwill?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q027.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that to love, considered as an act of charity , is nothing else than goodwill. For the Philosopher says (Rhet. ii, 4) that "to love is to wish a person well"; and this is goodwill. Therefore the act of char</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q027" target="st.ii-ii.q027.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q027.contains.st.ii-ii.q027.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q027.contains.st.ii-ii.q027.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q027</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.27 — The principle act of charity, which is to love</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q027.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.27 a.3 — Should God be loved for His own sake?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q027.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that God is loved out of charity , not for Himself but for the sake of something else. For Gregory says in a homily (In Evang. xi): "The soul learns from the things it knows , to love those it knows not," w</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q027" target="st.ii-ii.q027.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q027.contains.st.ii-ii.q027.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q027.contains.st.ii-ii.q027.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q027</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.27 — The principle act of charity, which is to love</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q027.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.27 a.4 — Can God be loved immediately in this life?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q027.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that God cannot be loved immediately in this life. For the "unknown cannot be loved" as Augustine says (De Trin. x, 1). Now we do not know God immediately in this life, since "we see now through a glass, in</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q027" target="st.ii-ii.q027.a005" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q027.contains.st.ii-ii.q027.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q027.contains.st.ii-ii.q027.a005</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q027</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.27 — The principle act of charity, which is to love</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q027.a005</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.27 a.5 — Can God be loved wholly?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q027.a005.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that God cannot be loved wholly. For love follows knowledge . Now God cannot be wholly known by us, since this would imply comprehension of Him. Therefore He cannot be wholly loved by us.</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q027" target="st.ii-ii.q027.a006" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q027.contains.st.ii-ii.q027.a006">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q027.contains.st.ii-ii.q027.a006</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q027</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.27 — The principle act of charity, which is to love</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q027.a006</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.27 a.6 — Is the love of God according to measure?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q027.a006.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that we ought to observe some mode in loving God . For the notion of good consists in mode, species and order, as Augustine states (De Nat. Boni iii, iv). Now the love of God is the best thing in man , acco</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q027" target="st.ii-ii.q027.a007" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q027.contains.st.ii-ii.q027.a007">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q027.contains.st.ii-ii.q027.a007</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q027</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.27 — The principle act of charity, which is to love</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q027.a007</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.27 a.7 — Which is the better, to love one's friend, or one's enemy?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q027.a007.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem more meritorious to love an enemy than to love a friend. For it is written ( Matthew 5:46 ): "If you love them that love you, what reward shall you have?" Therefore it is not deserving of reward to love one</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q027" target="st.ii-ii.q027.a008" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q027.contains.st.ii-ii.q027.a008">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q027.contains.st.ii-ii.q027.a008</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q027</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.27 — The principle act of charity, which is to love</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q027.a008</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.27 a.8 — Which is the better, to love God, or one's neighbor?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q027.a008.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that it is more meritorious to love one's neighbor than to love God . For the more meritorious thing would seem to be what the Apostle preferred. Now the Apostle preferred the love of our neighbor to the lo</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
