  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q029.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that peace is not the proper effect of charity . For one cannot have charity without sanctifying grace . But some have peace who have not sanctifying grace , thus heathens sometimes have peace. Therefore pe</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q029" target="st.ii-ii.q029.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q029.contains.st.ii-ii.q029.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q029.contains.st.ii-ii.q029.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q029</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.29 — Peace</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q029.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.29 a.4 — Is peace a virtue?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q029.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that peace is a virtue . For nothing is a matter of precept, unless it be an act of virtue . But there are precepts about keeping peace, for example: "Have peace among you" ( Mark 9:49 ). Therefore peace is</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q030" target="concept.charity" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q030.treated_in.concept.charity">
