<edge source="st.ii-ii.q030" target="st.ii-ii.q030.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q030.contains.st.ii-ii.q030.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q030.contains.st.ii-ii.q030.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q030</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.30 — Mercy</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q030.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.30 a.1 — Is evil the cause of mercy on the part of the person pitied?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q030.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that, properly speaking, evil is not the motive of mercy. For, as shown above ( II-II:19:1 ; I-II:79:1 ad 4 ; I:48:6 ), fault is an evil rather than punishment. Now fault provokes indignation rather than me</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q030" target="st.ii-ii.q030.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q030.contains.st.ii-ii.q030.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q030.contains.st.ii-ii.q030.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q030</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.30 — Mercy</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q030.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.30 a.2 — To whom does it belong to pity?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q030.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the reason for taking pity is not a defect in the person who takes pity. For it is proper to God to be merciful, wherefore it is written ( Psalm 144:9 ): "His tender mercies are over all His works." Bu</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q030" target="st.ii-ii.q030.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q030.contains.st.ii-ii.q030.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q030.contains.st.ii-ii.q030.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q030</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.30 — Mercy</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q030.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.30 a.3 — Is mercy a virtue?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q030.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that mercy is not a virtue . For the chief part of virtue is choice as the Philosopher states (Ethic. ii, 5). Now choice is "the desire of what has been already counselled" (Ethic. iii, 2). Therefore whatev</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q030" target="st.ii-ii.q030.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q030.contains.st.ii-ii.q030.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q030.contains.st.ii-ii.q030.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q030</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.30 — Mercy</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q030.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.30 a.4 — Is it the greatest of virtues?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
