  <data key="d17">general aspect of good , and this belongs to beneficence in general, and is an act of friendship, and, consequently, of charity : because the act of love includes goodwill whereby a man wishes his friend well, as stated above ( II-II:23:1 ; II-II:27:2 ). Now the will carries into effect</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q031" target="st.ii-ii.q031.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q031.contains.st.ii-ii.q031.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q031.contains.st.ii-ii.q031.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q031</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.31 — Beneficence</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q031.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.31 a.1 — Is beneficence an act of charity?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q031.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that beneficence is not an act of charity . For charity is chiefly directed to God . Now we cannot benefit God , according to Job 35:7 : "What shalt thou give Him? or what shall He receive of thy hand?" The</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q031" target="st.ii-ii.q031.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q031.contains.st.ii-ii.q031.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q031.contains.st.ii-ii.q031.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q031</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.31 — Beneficence</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q031.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.31 a.2 — Should we be beneficent to all?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q031.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that we are not bound to do good to all. For Augustine says (De Doctr. Christ. i, 28) that we "are unable to do good to everyone." Now virtue does not incline one to the impossible. Therefore it is not nece</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q031" target="st.ii-ii.q031.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q031.contains.st.ii-ii.q031.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q031.contains.st.ii-ii.q031.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q031</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.31 — Beneficence</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q031.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.31 a.3 — Should we be more beneficent to those who are more closely united to us?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q031.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that we are nor bound to do good to those rather who are more closely united to us. For it is written ( Luke 14:12 ): "When thou makest a dinner or a supper, call not thy friends, nor thy brethren, nor thy </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q031" target="st.ii-ii.q031.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q031.contains.st.ii-ii.q031.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q031.contains.st.ii-ii.q031.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q031</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.31 — Beneficence</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q031.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.31 a.4 — Is beneficence a special virtue?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q031.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that beneficence is a special virtue . For precepts are directed to virtue , since lawgivers purpose to make men virtuous (Ethic. i 9,13; ii, 1). Now beneficence and love are prescribed as distinct from one</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
