  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q032.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">f compassion and for God's sake," which motive belongs to mercy, as stated above ( II-II:30:2 ). Hence it is clear that almsgiving is, properly speaking, an act of mercy. This appears in its very name, for in Greek eleemosyne it is derived from having mercy eleein even as the Latin "misera</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q032" target="concept.charity" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q032.treated_in.concept.charity">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q032.treated_in.concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q032</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.32 — Almsdeeds</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d12">Charity</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q032-treated-in-concept-charity-st-ii-ii-q032-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q032.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">eek eleemosyne it is derived from having mercy eleein even as the Latin "miseratio" is. And since mercy is an effect of charity , as shown above ( 30, 2, 3, Objection 3 ), it follows that almsgiving is an act of charity through the medium of mercy.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q032" target="concept.mercy" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q032.treated_in.concept.mercy">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q032.treated_in.concept.mercy</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q032</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.32 — Almsdeeds</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.mercy</data>
  <data key="d12">Mercy</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q032-treated-in-concept-mercy-st-ii-ii-q032-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q032.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">s being "a deed whereby something is given to the needy, out of compassion and for God's sake," which motive belongs to mercy, as stated above ( II-II:30:2 ). Hence it is clear that almsgiving is, properly speaking, an act of mercy. This appears in its very name, for in Greek eleemosy</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q032" target="st.ii-ii.q032.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q032</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.32 — Almsdeeds</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q032.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.32 a.1 — Is almsgiving an act of charity?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q032.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that almsgiving is not an act of charity . For without charity one cannot do acts of charity . Now it is possible to give alms without having charity , according to 1 Corinthians 13:3 : "If I should distrib</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q032" target="st.ii-ii.q032.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q032</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.32 — Almsdeeds</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q032.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.32 a.2 — The different kinds of alms</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q032.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the different kinds of almsdeeds are unsuitably enumerated. For we reckon seven corporal almsdeeds , namely, to feed the hungry, to give drink to the thirsty, to clothe the naked, to harbor the harborl</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q032" target="st.ii-ii.q032.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q032</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.32 — Almsdeeds</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q032.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.32 a.3 — Which alms are of greater account, spiritual or corporal?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q032.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that corporal alms are of more account than spiritual alms . For it is more praiseworthy to give an alms to one who is in greater want, since an almsdeed is to be praised because it relieves one who is in n</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q032" target="st.ii-ii.q032.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q032</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.32 — Almsdeeds</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q032.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.32 a.4 — Do corporal alms have a spiritual effect?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q032.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that corporal almsdeeds have not a spiritual effect. For no effect exceeds its cause . But spiritual goods exceed corporal goods. Therefore corporal almsdeeds have no spiritual effect.</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q032" target="st.ii-ii.q032.a005" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a005</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q032</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.32 — Almsdeeds</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q032.a005</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.32 a.5 — Is the giving of alms a matter of precept?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q032.a005.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that almsgiving is not a matter of precept. For the counsels are distinct from the precepts. Now almsgiving is a matter of counsel, according to Daniel 4:24 : "Let my counsel be acceptable to the King; [ Vu</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q032" target="st.ii-ii.q032.a006" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a006">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a006</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q032</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.32 — Almsdeeds</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q032.a006</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.32 a.6 — Should corporal alms be given out of the things we need?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q032.a006.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that one ought not to give alms out of what one needs. For the order of charity should be observed not only as regards the effect of our benefactions but also as regards our interior affections. Now it is a</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q032" target="st.ii-ii.q032.a007" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a007">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a007</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q032</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.32 — Almsdeeds</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q032.a007</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.32 a.7 — Should corporal alms be given out of ill-gotten goods?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q032.a007.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that one may give alms out of ill-gotten goods. For it is written ( Luke 16:9 ): "Make unto you friends of the mammon of iniquity ." Now mammon signifies riches . Therefore it is lawful to make unto oneself</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q032" target="st.ii-ii.q032.a008" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a008">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a008</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q032</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.32 — Almsdeeds</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q032.a008</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.32 a.8 — Who can give alms?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q032.a008.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that one who is under another's power can give alms . For religious are under the power of their prelates to whom they have vowed obedience. Now if it were unlawful for them to give alms , they would lose b</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q032" target="st.ii-ii.q032.a009" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a009">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a009</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q032</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.32 — Almsdeeds</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q032.a009</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.32 a.9 — To whom should we give alms?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q032.a009.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that one ought not to give alms to those rather who are more closely united to us. For it is written ( Sirach 12:4-6 ): "Give to the merciful and uphold not the sinner . . . Do good to the humble and give n</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q032" target="st.ii-ii.q032.a010" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a010">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a010</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q032</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.32 — Almsdeeds</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q032.a010</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.32 a.10 — How should alms be given?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q032.a010.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that alms should not be given in abundance. For we ought to give alms to those chiefly who are most closely connected with us. But we ought not to give to them in such a way that they are likely to become r</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q033" target="concept.charity" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q033.treated_in.concept.charity">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q033.treated_in.concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q033</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.33 — Fraternal correction</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d12">Charity</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q033-treated-in-concept-charity-st-ii-ii-q033-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q033.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">ner. Now to do away with anyone's evil is the same as to procure his good : and to procure a person's good is an act of charity , whereby we wish and do our friend well. Consequently fraternal correction also is an act of charity , because thereby we drive out our brother's evil , viz.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q033" target="concept.fraternal_correction" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q033.treated_in.concept.fraternal_correction">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q033.treated_in.concept.fraternal_correction</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q033</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.33 — Fraternal correction</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.fraternal_correction</data>
  <data key="d12">Fraternal Correction</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q033-treated-in-concept-fraternal-correction-st-ii-ii-q033-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q033.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">n of a wrongdoer is twofold, one which applies a remedy to the sin considered as an evil of the sinner himself. This is fraternal correction properly so called, which is directed to the amendment of the sinner. Now to do away with anyone's evil is the same as to procure his good : and to procure a p</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q033" target="st.ii-ii.q033.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q033.contains.st.ii-ii.q033.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q033.contains.st.ii-ii.q033.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q033</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.33 — Fraternal correction</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q033.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.33 a.1 — Is fraternal correction an act of charity?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q033.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that fraternal correction is not an act of charity . For a gloss on Matthew 18:15 , "If thy brother shall offend against thee," says that "a man should reprove his brother out of zeal for justice ." But jus</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q033" target="st.ii-ii.q033.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q033.contains.st.ii-ii.q033.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q033.contains.st.ii-ii.q033.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q033</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.33 — Fraternal correction</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q033.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.33 a.2 — Is it a matter of precept?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q033.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that fraternal correction is not a matter of precept. For nothing impossible is a matter of precept, according to the saying of Jerome [Pelagius, Expos. Symb. ad Damas]: "Accursed be he who says that God ha</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q033" target="st.ii-ii.q033.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q033.contains.st.ii-ii.q033.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q033.contains.st.ii-ii.q033.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q033</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.33 — Fraternal correction</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q033.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.33 a.3 — Does this precept bind all, or only superiors?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q033.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that fraternal correction belongs to prelates alone. For Jerome [ Origen , Hom. vii in Joan.] says: "Let priests endeavor to fulfil this saying of the Gospel: 'If thy brother sin against thee,'" etc. Now pr</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q033" target="st.ii-ii.q033.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q033.contains.st.ii-ii.q033.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q033.contains.st.ii-ii.q033.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q033</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.33 — Fraternal correction</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q033.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.33 a.4 — Does this precept bind the subject to correct his superior?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q033.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that no man is bound to correct his prelate. For it is written ( Exodus 19:12 ): "The beast that shall touch the mount shall be stoned," [ Vulgate : 'Everyone that shall touch the mount, dying he shall die.</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q033" target="st.ii-ii.q033.a005" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q033.contains.st.ii-ii.q033.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q033.contains.st.ii-ii.q033.a005</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q033</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.33 — Fraternal correction</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q033.a005</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.33 a.5 — May a sinner correct anyone?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q033.a005.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that a sinner ought to reprove a wrongdoer. For no man is excused from obeying a precept by having committed a sin . But fraternal correction is a matter of precept, as stated above ( Article 2 ). Therefore</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q033" target="st.ii-ii.q033.a006" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q033.contains.st.ii-ii.q033.a006">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q033.contains.st.ii-ii.q033.a006</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q033</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.33 — Fraternal correction</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q033.a006</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.33 a.6 — Should one correct a person who becomes worse through being corrected?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q033.a006.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that one ought not to forbear from correcting someone through fear lest he become worse. For sin is weakness of the soul , according to Psalm 6:3 : "Have mercy on me, O Lord, for I am weak." Now he that has</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q033" target="st.ii-ii.q033.a007" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q033.contains.st.ii-ii.q033.a007">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q033.contains.st.ii-ii.q033.a007</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q033</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.33 — Fraternal correction</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q033.a007</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.33 a.7 — Should secret correction precede denouncement?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q033.a007.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the precept of fraternal correction does not demand that a private admonition should precede denunciation . For, in works of charity , we should above all follow the example of God , according to Ephes</data>
