  <data key="d12">II-II q.36 a.3 — Is it a mortal sin?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q036.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that envy is not a mortal sin . For since envy is a kind of sorrow, it is a passion of the sensitive appetite . Now there is no mortal sin in the sensuality, but only in the reason, as Augustine declares (D</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q036" target="st.ii-ii.q036.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q036.contains.st.ii-ii.q036.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q036.contains.st.ii-ii.q036.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q036</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.36 — Envy</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q036.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.36 a.4 — Is it a capital sin, and which are its daughters?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q036.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that envy is not a capital vice . For the capital vices are distinct from their daughters. Now envy is the daughter of vainglory; for the Philosopher says (Rhet. ii, 10) that "those who love honor and glory</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q037" target="concept.charity" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q037.treated_in.concept.charity">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q037.treated_in.concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q037</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.37 — Discord, which is contrary to peace</data>
