<edge source="st.ii-ii.q037" target="st.ii-ii.q037.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q037.contains.st.ii-ii.q037.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q037.contains.st.ii-ii.q037.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q037</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.37 — Discord, which is contrary to peace</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q037.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.37 a.1 — Is discord a sin?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q037.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that discord is not a sin . For to disaccord with man is to sever oneself from another's will. But this does not seem to be a sin , because God's will alone, and not our neighbor's, is the rule of our own w</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q037" target="st.ii-ii.q037.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q037.contains.st.ii-ii.q037.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q037.contains.st.ii-ii.q037.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q037</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.37 — Discord, which is contrary to peace</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q037.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.37 a.2 — Is it a daughter of vainglory?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q037.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that discord is not a daughter of vainglory. For anger is a vice distinct from vainglory. Now discord is apparently the daughter of anger , according to Proverbs 15:18 : "A passionate man stirreth up strife</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q038" target="concept.contention" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q038.treated_in.concept.contention">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q038.treated_in.concept.contention</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q038</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.38 — Contention</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.contention</data>
  <data key="d12">Contention</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q038-treated-in-concept-contention-st-ii-ii-q038-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q038.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">To contend is to tend against some one. Wherefore just as discord denotes a contrariety of wills, so contention signifies contrariety of speech. For this reason when a man contrasts various contrary things in a speech, this is called "contentio," which Tully calls one of</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q038" target="st.ii-ii.q038.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q038.contains.st.ii-ii.q038.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q038.contains.st.ii-ii.q038.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q038</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.38 — Contention</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q038.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.38 a.1 — Is contention a mortal sin?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q038.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that contention is not a mortal sin . For there is no mortal sin in spiritual men: and yet contention is to be found in them, according to Luke 22:24 : "And there was also a strife amongst" the disciples of</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q038" target="st.ii-ii.q038.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q038.contains.st.ii-ii.q038.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q038.contains.st.ii-ii.q038.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q038</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.38 — Contention</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q038.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.38 a.2 — Is it a daughter of vainglory?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q038.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that contention is not a daughter of vainglory. For contention is akin to zeal, wherefore it is written ( 1 Corinthians 3:3 ): "Whereas there is among you zeal [ Douay : 'envying'] and contention, are you n</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q039" target="concept.charity" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q039.treated_in.concept.charity">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q039.treated_in.concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q039</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.39 — Schism</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d12">Charity</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q039-treated-in-concept-charity-st-ii-ii-q039-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q039.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">ing, a special sin , for the reason that the schismatic intends to sever himself from that unity which is the effect of charity : because charity unites not only one person to another with the bond of spiritual love, but also the whole Church in unity of spirit. Accordingly schismatics</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q039" target="concept.ecclesial_unity" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q039.treated_in.concept.ecclesial_unity">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q039.treated_in.concept.ecclesial_unity</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q039</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.39 — Schism</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.ecclesial_unity</data>
  <data key="d12">Ecclesial Unity</data>
  <data key="d13">doctrine</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q039-treated-in-concept-ecclesial-unity-st-ii-ii-q039-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q039.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">irit. Accordingly schismatics properly so called are those who, wilfully and intentionally separate themselves from the unity of the Church ; for this is the chief unity, and the particular unity of several individuals among themselves is subordinate to the unity of the Church , even as the mutual</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q039" target="concept.schism" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q039.treated_in.concept.schism">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q039.treated_in.concept.schism</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q039</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.39 — Schism</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.schism</data>
  <data key="d12">Schism</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q039-treated-in-concept-schism-st-ii-ii-q039-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q039.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As Isidore says (Etym. viii, 3), schism takes its name "from being a scission of minds," and scission is opposed to unity. Wherefore the sin of schism is one that is directly and essentially opposed</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q039" target="st.ii-ii.q039.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q039.contains.st.ii-ii.q039.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q039.contains.st.ii-ii.q039.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q039</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.39 — Schism</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q039.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.39 a.1 — Is schism a special sin?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q039.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that schism is not a special sin . For " schism ," as Pope Pelagius I says (Epist. ad Victor. et Pancrat.), "denotes a division." But every sin causes a division, according to Isaiah 59 : "Your sins have di</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q039" target="st.ii-ii.q039.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q039.contains.st.ii-ii.q039.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q039.contains.st.ii-ii.q039.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q039</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.39 — Schism</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q039.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.39 a.2 — Is it graver than unbelief?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q039.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that schism is a graver sin than unbelief. For the graver sin meets with a graver punishment, according to Deuteronomy 25:2 : "According to the measure of the sin shall the measure also of the stripes be." </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q039" target="st.ii-ii.q039.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q039.contains.st.ii-ii.q039.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q039.contains.st.ii-ii.q039.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q039</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.39 — Schism</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q039.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.39 a.3 — The power exercised by schismatics</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q039.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that schismatics have some power. For Augustine says (Contra Donat. i, 1): "Just as those who come back to the Church after being baptized , are not baptized again, so those who return after being ordained,</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q039" target="st.ii-ii.q039.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q039.contains.st.ii-ii.q039.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q039.contains.st.ii-ii.q039.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q039</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.39 — Schism</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q039.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.39 a.4 — The punishment inflicted on them</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q039.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that schismatics are not rightly punished with excommunication . For excommunication deprives a man chiefly of a share in the sacraments . But Augustine says (Contra Donat. vi, 5) that " Baptism can be rece</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q040" target="concept.common_good" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q040.treated_in.concept.common_good">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q040.treated_in.concept.common_good</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q040</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.40 — War</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.common_good</data>
  <data key="d12">Common Good</data>
  <data key="d13">end</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q040-treated-in-concept-common-good-st-ii-ii-q040-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q040.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">In order for a war to be just , three things are necessary . First, the authority of the sovereign by whose command the war is to be waged. For it is not the business of a private individual to declare war , because he can seek for redress of his rights from t</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q040" target="concept.war" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q040.treated_in.concept.war">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q040.treated_in.concept.war</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q040</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.40 — War</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.war</data>
  <data key="d12">War</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q040-treated-in-concept-war-st-ii-ii-q040-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q040.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">In order for a war to be just , three things are necessary . First, the authority of the sovereign by whose command the war is to be waged. For it is not the business of a privat</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q040" target="st.ii-ii.q040.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q040.contains.st.ii-ii.q040.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q040.contains.st.ii-ii.q040.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q040</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.40 — War</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q040.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.40 a.1 — Is some kind of war lawful?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q040.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that it is always sinful to wage war . Because punishment is not inflicted except for sin . Now those who wage war are threatened by Our Lord with punishment, according to Matthew 26:52 : "All that take the</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q040" target="st.ii-ii.q040.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q040.contains.st.ii-ii.q040.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q040.contains.st.ii-ii.q040.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q040</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.40 — War</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q040.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.40 a.2 — Is it lawful for clerics to fight?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q040.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem lawful for clerics and bishops to fight. For, as stated above ( Article 1 ), wars are lawful and just in so far as they protect the poor and the entire common weal from suffering at the hands of the foe. No</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q040" target="st.ii-ii.q040.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q040.contains.st.ii-ii.q040.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q040.contains.st.ii-ii.q040.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q040</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.40 — War</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q040.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.40 a.3 — Is it lawful for belligerents to lay ambushes?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q040.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that it is unlawful to lay ambushes in war . For it is written ( Deuteronomy 16:20 ): "Thou shalt follow justly after that which is just." But ambushes, since they are a kind of deception, seem to pertain t</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q040" target="st.ii-ii.q040.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q040.contains.st.ii-ii.q040.a004">
