  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q044.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.44 a.1 — Should precepts be given about charity?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q044.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that no precept should be given about charity . For charity imposes the mode on all acts of virtue , since it is the form of the virtues as stated above ( II-II:23:8 ), while the precepts are about the virt</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q044" target="st.ii-ii.q044.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q044.contains.st.ii-ii.q044.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q044.contains.st.ii-ii.q044.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q044</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.44 — The precepts of charity</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q044.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.44 a.2 — Should there be one or two?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q044.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that there should not have been given two precepts of charity . For the precepts of the Law are directed to virtue , as stated above ( Article 1, Objection 3 ). Now charity is one virtue , as shown above ( </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q044" target="st.ii-ii.q044.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q044.contains.st.ii-ii.q044.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q044.contains.st.ii-ii.q044.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q044</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.44 — The precepts of charity</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q044.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.44 a.3 — Do two suffice?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q044.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that two precepts of charity do not suffice. For precepts are given about acts of virtue . Now acts are distinguished by their objects. Since, then, man is bound to love four things out of charity , namely,</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q044" target="st.ii-ii.q044.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q044.contains.st.ii-ii.q044.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q044.contains.st.ii-ii.q044.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q044</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.44 — The precepts of charity</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q044.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.44 a.4 — Is it fittingly prescribed that we should love God, "with thy whole heart"?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q044.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that it is unfittingly commanded that man should love God with his whole heart. For the mode of a virtuous act is not a matter of precept, as shown above ( Article 1, Reply to Objection 1 ; I-II:100:9 ). No</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q044" target="st.ii-ii.q044.a005" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q044.contains.st.ii-ii.q044.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q044.contains.st.ii-ii.q044.a005</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q044</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.44 — The precepts of charity</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q044.a005</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.44 a.5 — Is it fittingly added: "With thy whole mind," etc.?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q044.a005.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that it was unfitting to the words, "Thou shalt love the Lord thy God , with thy whole heart," to add, "and with thy whole soul , and with thy whole strength" ( Deuteronomy 6:5 ). For heart does not mean he</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q044" target="st.ii-ii.q044.a006" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q044.contains.st.ii-ii.q044.a006">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q044.contains.st.ii-ii.q044.a006</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q044</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.44 — The precepts of charity</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q044.a006</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.44 a.6 — Is it possible to fulfil this precept in this life?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q044.a006.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that in this life it is possible to fulfil this precept of the love of God . For according to Jerome [Pelagius, Exposit. Cath. Fid.] " accursed is he who says that God has commanded anything impossible." Bu</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q044" target="st.ii-ii.q044.a007" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q044.contains.st.ii-ii.q044.a007">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q044.contains.st.ii-ii.q044.a007</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q044</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.44 — The precepts of charity</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q044.a007</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.44 a.7 — The precept: "Thou shalt love thy neighbor as thyself"</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q044.a007.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the precept of the love of our neighbor is unfittingly expressed. For the love of charity extends to all men , even to our enemies, as may be seen in Matthew 5:44 . But the word "neighbor" denotes a ki</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q044" target="st.ii-ii.q044.a008" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q044.contains.st.ii-ii.q044.a008">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q044.contains.st.ii-ii.q044.a008</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q044</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.44 — The precepts of charity</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q044.a008</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.44 a.8 — Is the order of charity included in the precept?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q044.a008.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the order of charity is not included in the precept. For whoever transgresses a precept does a wrong. But if man loves some one as much as he ought, and loves any other man more, he wrongs no man . The</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q045" target="concept.beatitude_peacemakers" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q045.treated_in.concept.beatitude_peacemakers">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q045.treated_in.concept.beatitude_peacemakers</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q045</data>
