  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q045.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">t only learns, but is patient of, Divine things." Now this sympathy or connaturality for Divine things is the result of charity , which unites us to God , according to 1 Corinthians 6:17 : "He who is joined to the Lord, is one spirit." Consequently wisdom which is a gift , has its cause</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q045" target="concept.wisdom_gift" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q045.treated_in.concept.wisdom_gift">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q045.treated_in.concept.wisdom_gift</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q045</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.45 — The gift of wisdom</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.wisdom_gift</data>
  <data key="d12">Gift of Wisdom</data>
  <data key="d13">gift_holy_spirit</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q045-treated-in-concept-wisdom-gift-st-ii-ii-q045-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q045.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">According to the Philosopher (Metaph. i: 2), it belongs to wisdom to consider the highest cause . By means of that cause we are able to form a most certain judgment about other causes , and according thereto all things should be set in order. Now the highest c</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q045" target="st.ii-ii.q045.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q045.contains.st.ii-ii.q045.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q045.contains.st.ii-ii.q045.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q045</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.45 — The gift of wisdom</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q045.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.45 a.1 — Should wisdom be reckoned among the gifts of the Holy Ghost?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q045.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that wisdom ought not to be reckoned among the gifts of the Holy Ghost . For the gifts are more perfect than the virtues , as stated above ( I-II:68:8 ). Now virtue is directed to the good alone, wherefore </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q045" target="st.ii-ii.q045.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q045.contains.st.ii-ii.q045.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q045.contains.st.ii-ii.q045.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q045</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.45 — The gift of wisdom</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q045.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.45 a.2 — What is its subject?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q045.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that wisdom is not in the intellect as its subject. For Augustine says (Ep. cxx) that "wisdom is the charity of God ." Now charity is in the will as its subject, and not in the intellect , as stated above (</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q045" target="st.ii-ii.q045.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q045.contains.st.ii-ii.q045.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q045.contains.st.ii-ii.q045.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q045</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.45 — The gift of wisdom</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q045.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.45 a.3 — Is wisdom only speculative or also practical?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q045.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that wisdom is not practical but merely speculative. For the gift of wisdom is more excellent than the wisdom which is an intellectual virtue . But wisdom, as an intellectual virtue , is merely speculative.</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q045" target="st.ii-ii.q045.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q045.contains.st.ii-ii.q045.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q045.contains.st.ii-ii.q045.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q045</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.45 — The gift of wisdom</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q045.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.45 a.4 — Is the wisdom that is a gift compatible with mortal sin?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q045.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that wisdom can be without grace and with mortal sin . For saints glory chiefly in such things as are incompatible with mortal sin , according to 2 Corinthians 1:12 : "Our glory is this, the testimony of ou</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q045" target="st.ii-ii.q045.a005" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q045.contains.st.ii-ii.q045.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q045.contains.st.ii-ii.q045.a005</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q045</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.45 — The gift of wisdom</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q045.a005</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.45 a.5 — Is it in all those who have sanctifying grace?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q045.a005.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that wisdom is not in all who have grace . For it is more to have wisdom than to hear wisdom. Now it is only for the perfect to hear wisdom, according to 1 Corinthians 2:6 : "We speak wisdom among the perfe</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q045" target="st.ii-ii.q045.a006" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q045.contains.st.ii-ii.q045.a006">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q045.contains.st.ii-ii.q045.a006</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q045</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.45 — The gift of wisdom</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q045.a006</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.45 a.6 — Which beatitude corresponds to it?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q045.a006.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It seems that the seventh beatitude does not correspond to the gift of wisdom. For the seventh beatitude is: "Blessed are the peacemakers, for they shall be called the children of God ." Now both these things belong to c</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q046" target="concept.folly" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q046.treated_in.concept.folly">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q046.treated_in.concept.folly</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q046</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.46 — Folly which is opposed to wisdom</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.folly</data>
  <data key="d12">Folly</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q046-treated-in-concept-folly-st-ii-ii-q046-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q046.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Stultitia [Folly] seems to take its name from "stupor"; wherefore Isidore says (Etym. x, under the letter of S): "A fool is one who through dullness [stuporem] remains unmoved.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q046" target="concept.wisdom_gift" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q046.treated_in.concept.wisdom_gift">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q046.treated_in.concept.wisdom_gift</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q046</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.46 — Folly which is opposed to wisdom</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.wisdom_gift</data>
  <data key="d12">Gift of Wisdom</data>
  <data key="d13">gift_holy_spirit</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q046-treated-in-concept-wisdom-gift-st-ii-ii-q046-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q046.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Stultitia [Folly] seems to take its name from "stupor"; wherefore Isidore says (Etym. x, under the letter of S): "A fool is one who through dullness [stuporem] remains unmoved." And folly differs from fatuity, according to the same authority (Etym. x), in that</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q046" target="st.ii-ii.q046.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q046.contains.st.ii-ii.q046.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q046.contains.st.ii-ii.q046.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q046</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.46 — Folly which is opposed to wisdom</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q046.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.46 a.1 — Is folly contrary to wisdom?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q046.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that folly is not contrary to wisdom. For seemingly unwisdom is directly opposed to wisdom. But folly does not seem to be the same as unwisdom, for the latter is apparently about Divine things alone, wherea</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q046" target="st.ii-ii.q046.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q046.contains.st.ii-ii.q046.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q046.contains.st.ii-ii.q046.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q046</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.46 — Folly which is opposed to wisdom</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q046.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.46 a.2 — Is folly a sin?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q046.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that folly is not a sin . For no sin arises in us from nature . But some are fools naturally . Therefore folly is not a sin .</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q046" target="st.ii-ii.q046.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q046.contains.st.ii-ii.q046.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q046.contains.st.ii-ii.q046.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q046</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.46 — Folly which is opposed to wisdom</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q046.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.46 a.3 — To which capital sin is it reducible?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q046.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that folly is not a daughter of lust . For Gregory (Moral. xxxi, 45) enumerates the daughters of lust , among which however he makes no mention of folly. Therefore folly does not proceed from lust .</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q001.a001" target="concept.faith" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q001.a001.treated_in.concept.faith">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q001.a001.treated_in.concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q001.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.1 a.1 — Is the object of faith the First Truth?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d12">Faith</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q001-a001-treated-in-concept-faith-st-ii-ii-q001-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q001.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Accordingly if we consider, in faith , the formal aspect of the object, it is nothing else than the First Truth</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
